N2  - The purpose of this paper is to clarify the meaning of ‘Xiang’(相) mentioned in the Treatise on Awakening Mahāyāna Faith(大乘起信論). To clarify the meaning of Xiang, I searched for meaning of Xiang influenced the Treatise on Awakening Mahāyāna Faith in chronological order. Chapter II points out the difference of lakṣaṇa and nimitta, which are the Sanskrit words that ‘Xiang’(相) originated from. Lakṣaṇa means characteristics or attributes of an object. Nimitta means representations in consciousness. They are different because lakṣaṇa exists outside consciousness, but nimitta exists within consciousness. Chapter III shows the history of ‘Xiang’(相). In the second half of the 2nd century, An Shigao(安世高) and Lokasema(支婁迦懺) translated both lakṣaṇa and nimitta as ‘Xiang’. In the 4th century, Kumārajīva(鳩摩羅什) used ‘Xiang’ to mean unreal image(非實相). This was originated from the meaning of lakṣaṇa. But in the 6th century, after the Yogācāra Buddhism was introduced to China, the meaning of ‘Xiang’ was focused on nimitta. Because nimitta is more frequently used in Yogācāra Buddhism. These two ‘Xiang’ are used both in the Treatise on Awakening Mahāyāna Faith. ‘Xiang’ as nimitta is used as ‘external object’(境界相). ‘Xiang’ as lakṣaṇa is used as ‘characteristic’(差別相). Chapter IV analyzed the interpretation of ‘Xiang’(相) in Wonhyo(元曉) and Fazang(法藏)’s commentary of the Treatise on Awakening Mahāyāna Faith. Wonhyo interprets the ‘Xiang’ as ‘external object’(境界相), which means nimitta. But, Fazang interprets ‘Xiang’ to appearance, which originated from lakṣaṇa. From this difference, I can put forward a new hypothesis that could explain the difference between Wonhyo and Fazang’s annotation of the Treatise on Awakening Mahāyāna Faith. That is, their difference on annotation is from the difference of interpretation of ‘Xiang’.
